---
title: Yeshie — What Happens When a Task Runs
---
sequenceDiagram
    actor Mike as Mike / Claude
    participant Bridge as cc-bridge MCP
    participant Relay as Relay Server<br/>:3333
    participant Ext as Chrome Extension<br/>Background Worker
    participant Tab as Browser Tab<br/>app.yeshid.com

    Note over Mike,Tab: Example task: "Modify John Smith — new email: john@newco.com"

    Mike->>Bridge: yeshie_run(payload_path, params)
    Bridge->>Relay: HTTP POST /run<br/>{ payload: {...}, params: {user_identifier:"John Smith", new_personal_email:"john@newco.com"} }

    Relay->>Ext: WebSocket: emit("run", payload)
    Note over Ext: Receives task,<br/>begins chain execution

    rect rgb(237, 233, 254)
        Note over Ext,Tab: Step 1 — Navigate
        Ext->>Tab: Navigate to /organization/people
        Tab-->>Ext: Page loaded ✓
    end

    rect rgb(237, 233, 254)
        Note over Ext,Tab: Step 2 — Find & type in search box
        Ext->>Tab: executeScript: find input[placeholder='Search']
        Tab-->>Ext: Element found (confidence: 0.90)
        Ext->>Tab: debugger.Input.insertText("John Smith")
        Tab-->>Ext: List filtered to John Smith ✓
    end

    rect rgb(237, 233, 254)
        Note over Ext,Tab: Step 3 — Click John's name
        Ext->>Tab: executeScript: find row containing "John Smith", click it
        Tab-->>Ext: Navigated to /organization/people/{uuid} ✓
    end

    rect rgb(237, 233, 254)
        Note over Ext,Tab: Steps 4–12 — Click Edit, find fields, update email, Confirm
        Ext->>Tab: (multiple steps: click Edit button, find email field,<br/>clear old value, type new value, click Confirm)
        Tab-->>Ext: "Workflow created." snackbar visible ✓
    end

    Ext->>Relay: WebSocket: emit("result", ChainResult)
    Note over Ext,Relay: ChainResult includes:<br/>• success: true<br/>• steps completed: 14<br/>• resolved selectors (what actually worked)<br/>• duration: 8.4s

    Relay->>Bridge: HTTP response: ChainResult JSON
    Bridge->>Mike: Task complete ✓

    Note over Mike,Tab: After the run, improve.js merges the<br/>resolved selectors back into the payload file.<br/>Next run will be faster (uses cached selectors).
